7. Modifications Made

Added additional LEDs for extended binary display

Updated GPIO definitions

Added runtime task statistics

Added heap monitoring

Improved debug output

8. SOP – Standard Operating Procedure

Connect LEDs to the Pico GPIO pins with resistors

Build the project using Pico SDK

Flash the firmware to the Pico

Connect USB and open a serial monitor (115200 baud)

Observe:

Status LED blinking

Binary values displayed on LEDs

Runtime statistics printed every 3 seconds

9. Q&A

Q: Why FreeRTOS?
A: FreeRTOS enables real-time multitasking and better system organization.

Q: Why add more LEDs?
A: To improve binary visualization and extend the exercise functionality.

Q: What is the Stack High Water Mark?
A: It shows the minimum unused stack space, helping prevent stack overflow.

Q: Why mask random value with 0x0F?
A: To limit the random number to 4 bits for controlled LED output.

10. Comments & Notes

Always use resistors with LEDs

Heap statistics help debug memory issues

Suitable for learning FreeRTOS on microcontrollers

Code runs on core 0 only

11. Final Comment

This project demonstrates practical FreeRTOS usage, GPIO control, and system monitoring on the Raspberry Pi Pico.
The addition of extra LEDs enhances learning and visualization of binary data.
